01:45:14,958 --> 01:45:22,101
So I'm going to transition just a little bit and put on my scholarly hat and turn to the concept of care.

642
01:45:23,281 --> 01:45:24,942
In an article by Christina Sharpe,

643
01:45:26,196 --> 01:45:30,817
called In to Survive, she says that care is a shared risk.

644
01:45:31,678 --> 01:45:34,979
This shared risk to me relates to many of the teachings of Dr. King.

645
01:45:35,539 --> 01:45:43,401
When speaking of the sanitation workers again, he asserts, the question is not, if I stop to help this man in need, what will happen to me?

646
01:45:44,021 --> 01:45:49,162
The question is, if I do not stop to help the sanitation workers, what will happen to them?

647
01:45:49,763 --> 01:45:50,803
That is the question.

648
01:45:51,922 --> 01:45:55,944
He goes on to say, let us rise up with a greater readiness.

649
01:45:56,404 --> 01:45:58,525
Let us stand with a greater determination.

650
01:45:58,925 --> 01:46:05,227
And let us move on in these powerful days, these days to challenge to make America what it ought to be.

651
01:46:05,708 --> 01:46:09,069
We have an opportunity to make America a better nation.

652
01:46:10,489 --> 01:46:21,634
So for me, a part of understanding American history, a part of getting to that moment where the country can be a better nation, is to seriously grapple with the history of slavery.

653
01:46:22,121 --> 01:46:29,983
and the contributions that enslaved people made to building the wealth of this country, but also to building the wealth of right here in Massachusetts.

654
01:46:31,444 --> 01:46:35,765
Working in the field of slavery asks us all to bear witness.

655
01:46:36,486 --> 01:46:50,690
Bear witness to both the unimaginable violence, but also to bear witness to the ways in which enslaved people, women, men, and children resisted, created lives for themselves, experienced joy, perished, and survived.

656
01:46:51,422 --> 01:46:55,063
To hold all of these things simultaneously takes care.

657
01:46:55,663 --> 01:47:01,004
It asks us today, how not only do we care for the living, but how do we care for the dead?

658
01:47:01,905 --> 01:47:05,025
It takes the ability to go into archives and to look.

659
01:47:05,605 --> 01:47:11,607
Look through box after box in hopes of finding documents that provide us with a trace of enslaved people.

660
01:47:12,167 --> 01:47:13,667
Sometimes we find a sentence.

661
01:47:14,128 --> 01:47:17,308
In the case of Belinda Sutton, we find a wealth of petitions.

662
01:47:17,848 --> 01:47:20,109
But we always find something when we look.

663
01:47:20,749 --> 01:47:28,511
When we ask different questions, we begin to imagine a world in which enslaved people not only inhabited, but they also shaped.

664
01:47:29,431 --> 01:47:40,994
We learn about their multiple attempts of running away to be reunited with their family, the kinship networks they created, and the protests that they had for the peculiar institution of slavery.

665
01:47:42,034 --> 01:47:48,876
We learn enslavers placed enslaved people as the heads of their estates in order to resist their properties being seized during war.

666
01:47:49,507 --> 01:47:52,448
We are forced also to contend with family separations.

667
01:47:52,848 --> 01:47:58,131
We are forced to think about the ways in which children were a part of the institution as well.

668
01:47:59,231 --> 01:48:05,494
However, violence is never the cornerstone of enslaved people's history, to quote Marissa Fuentes.

669
01:48:07,435 --> 01:48:15,378
Sadia Hartman writes, write our now as if it is interrupted by this past, and to imagine a free state.

670
01:48:15,889 --> 01:48:22,232
not as a time before captivity or slavery, but rather as the anticipated future of this writing.

671
01:48:23,512 --> 01:48:32,636
For me, no one is more instructive of that than Belinda Sutton, who was enslaved by the royals at the royal house plantation.

672
01:48:34,037 --> 01:48:43,501
Belinda Sutton first enters the historical archive on August 14, 1768, when her name appears simply as Belinda in Medford Vital Records.

673
01:48:44,688 --> 01:48:47,069
Those records show the baptism of her children.

674
01:48:48,270 --> 01:48:53,333
The next time we meet Belinda Sutton is in 1781 through Isaac Royal, Jr.'

675
01:48:53,313 --> 01:48:53,673
's will.

676
01:48:54,414 --> 01:49:04,499
In his will, he states, I do also give unto my stepdaughter, Mary Royal Irving, my Negro woman, Belinda, in the case that she does not choose her freedom.

677
01:49:05,220 --> 01:49:14,305
If she does choose her freedom, provided that she gets security, that she shall not be a charge to the town of Medford.

678
01:49:15,717 --> 01:49:24,426
In 1783, we meet Belinda again, but this time as a member of Massachusetts' relatively small but bustling free population.

679
01:49:25,267 --> 01:49:35,717
After obtaining her freedom, Belinda Sutton petitions the Massachusetts General Court in 1783 for a pension from the royal estate in order to support herself and her sick daughter.

680
01:49:37,158 --> 01:49:39,280
Belinda's petition is shockingly approved.

681
01:49:39,788 --> 01:49:48,915
And she's awarded an annual pension of 15 pounds and 12 shillings, becoming one of the earliest and most significant examples of reparations in this country.

682
01:49:50,605 --> 01:49:52,966
So what do we do with stories like Belinda?

683
01:49:53,326 --> 01:49:55,007
Well, we should talk about them.

684
01:49:55,467 --> 01:49:56,588
We should know about them.

685
01:49:57,188 --> 01:49:58,729
It is a part of our local history.

686
01:49:59,029 --> 01:50:08,913
But also, they represent a testament to the long history of black activism, of black women's activism, of black women's legal activism.

687
01:50:09,253 --> 01:50:12,975
So I know we're in Massachusetts, where we always talk about the revolution.

688
01:50:13,355 --> 01:50:18,297
But when we talk about the revolution, we have to also have a different conversation about what is freedom.

689
01:50:18,716 --> 01:50:22,279
Freedom did not mean the same thing for everyone at that time.

690
01:50:22,619 --> 01:50:32,348
And when you study and when you learn about the enslaved people and the free black people in Massachusetts, what you realize is that they were creating definitions of freedom for themselves.

691
01:50:32,988 --> 01:50:44,458
And this is what, for me, Dr. King is very instructive about, thinking about our history to not only imagine what it means to think about what it means to be free, but also

692
01:50:45,176 --> 01:50:49,737
being able to rely on the people who came before us, who set the pathway.

693
01:50:51,598 --> 01:50:57,940
So I'm going to go ahead and skip, because I feel like I'm running over time.

694
01:50:58,360 --> 01:51:12,985
But as historic sites and museums and different organizations embark on the journey to reckon with the histories of slavery, which really does come out of

695
01:51:13,388 --> 01:51:18,633
this post-George Floyd moment in many, many ways, especially here in Massachusetts.

696
01:51:18,653 --> 01:51:24,998
There is not an institution who is not studying their history and their connection to slavery right now, which is great.

697
01:51:26,520 --> 01:51:33,726
But in doing this work, one of the things that I ask people to do is to continuously look.

698
01:51:34,206 --> 01:51:40,572
And when you think you can't find anything else, to look again, to think about the archive, to ask new questions,

699
01:51:40,965 --> 01:51:57,011
to imagine a world that always centers black people as political agents, to tell new stories, to work with descendant communities, to also talk about the ways in which the afterlives of slavery manifest in systemic racism every single day.

700
01:51:58,791 --> 01:52:03,813
And when you think you know everything that you can know, I always say, look and look again.

701
01:52:04,393 --> 01:52:09,655
Because to care means to do the work, even when it's hard, and even when it seems impossible.

702
01:52:12,813 --> 01:52:17,176
In Tales from the Haunted South, Taya Miles reflects on her fascination with historic homes.

703
01:52:17,936 --> 01:52:22,079
She says, I am haunted by homes of the past and the people who occupy them.

704
01:52:23,419 --> 01:52:31,584
As someone who runs a historic house museum, I too am haunted by homes of the past and the people who occupy them.

705
01:52:32,304 --> 01:52:40,189
However, lately, I've found myself haunted by the people, the descendants of slavery, who never stepped foot into the homes of the past, because some museums

706
01:52:40,702 --> 01:52:50,327
continue to erase them for the sake of locating this history as part of an American shameful past instead of reckoning with how the legacy of slavery is all around us today.

707
01:52:52,348 --> 01:53:03,794
So I'll end with saying that one of my goals is not only to give people the tools to understand the history, but also to give people the tools to reckon with their current moment today.

708
01:53:04,415 --> 01:53:10,578
We absolutely cannot care about black people's freedom dreams in the past if we actually do not care about their freedom.

709
01:53:43,831 --> 01:53:53,979
Thank you, Kiara, for bringing wonderful additional perspective and context to today's celebration.

710
01:53:54,640 --> 01:54:02,106
Thank you for coming as you always do with the real and the sincere and not sugarcoating it.

711
01:54:02,626 --> 01:54:03,767
We appreciate you.

712
01:54:04,357 --> 01:54:06,819
And we're blessed by your joining us today.

713
01:54:13,903 --> 01:54:30,372
So it is our sincere hope that folks who have not yet visited the museum and slave quarters, when it opens back up in the spring, will take full advantage of the great history that you preserve right here in our own backyard.

714
01:54:31,063 --> 01:54:43,086
And I know that one of the things that Lisa and I have talked about is that we definitely plan on doing is putting a trip together from the community center and bringing folks over to the museum so that they can get the full tour.

715
01:54:44,326 --> 01:54:45,526
All right, thank you so much.

716
01:54:48,047 --> 01:54:53,168
So I thought a lot about what poem that I would share with you today.

717
01:54:53,548 --> 01:54:57,069
You know, they got this thing in Medford now called Poet Laureate.

718
01:55:04,223 --> 01:55:06,665
It comes to my recollection, it's never happened before.

719
01:55:07,085 --> 01:55:15,590
And for it to happen with me, a brother from West Medford, who could have figured that?

720
01:55:16,591 --> 01:55:22,355
In any case, I want to read a piece called A Call to Action.

721
01:55:24,576 --> 01:55:29,459
In big cities and small towns alike, America sees a dangerous spike.

722
01:55:29,579 --> 01:55:33,162
Violent intent has reemerged as purveyors

723
01:55:33,798 --> 01:55:40,261
Lies and hate converge to weave a dark and angry story and rob the flag of all its glory.

724
01:55:41,362 --> 01:55:43,943
We are called warriors in this fight.

725
01:55:44,624 --> 01:55:51,747
Let us coalesce and get things right and battle for a common goal that speaks to our collective soul.

726
01:55:52,428 --> 01:55:57,671
Advancing the causes of truth and peace, striving to make the outrage cease.

727
01:55:58,591 --> 01:56:00,352
That's the call of allyship.

728
01:56:00,883 --> 01:56:08,086
an anchor for this human trip, not a political bargaining chip, a dialogue chain to pull and rip.

729
01:56:09,127 --> 01:56:14,909
When the village gathers to raise a barn, everyone eats good food from the farm.

730
01:56:14,949 --> 01:56:20,892
When the village gathers to raise its young, no hate speech is on its tongue.

731
01:56:21,872 --> 01:56:24,033
Dr. King called for beloved community.

732
01:56:24,515 --> 01:56:26,656
Faith and grace and love and unity.

733
01:56:27,316 --> 01:56:35,160
Can these fragrant oils grant us immunity when all around us folks hate our kinship, strange and weak?

734
01:56:35,920 --> 01:56:40,982
Let us not allow their prideful rages to force us into a thousand cages.

735
01:56:41,563 --> 01:56:47,565
Let's put our smaller wants aside and be the voice that's unified.

736
01:56:48,226 --> 01:56:50,567
We can begin right where we are.

737
01:56:51,127 --> 01:56:53,228
We can let Medford raise the bar.

738
01:56:53,757 --> 01:56:57,738
We can show a fractured land a hopeful future that's now at hand.

739
01:56:58,678 --> 01:57:00,198
Look to make a friend today.

740
01:57:01,179 --> 01:57:03,519
To gather together, and yes, to pray.

741
01:57:04,139 --> 01:57:09,300
Regardless of which God you serve, touch a heart and strike a nerve.

742
01:57:10,161 --> 01:57:12,661
Such was the choice that Martin made.

743
01:57:13,401 --> 01:57:15,882
And for that choice, he dearly paid.

744
01:57:16,702 --> 01:57:21,323
Let's make sure his sacrifice steers the ship that breaks the ice.

745
01:57:22,059 --> 01:57:24,863
We're all called warriors in this fight.

746
01:57:25,624 --> 01:57:40,562
Let us coalesce to get things right and battle for a common goal that speaks to our collective soul, advancing the causes of truth and peace, striving to make the outrage cease.

747
01:57:41,654 --> 01:57:48,240
When this village gathers as Medford Strong, as beloved cousins, let's get along.

748
01:57:48,901 --> 01:57:54,626
Across the borders of neighborhood, let's be about the common good.

749
01:57:55,306 --> 01:57:58,329
We're all called warriors in this fight.

750
01:57:58,890 --> 01:58:03,554
Let's walk in peace and truth and light.

751
01:58:34,389 --> 01:58:44,955
your spirits toward participation in our ongoing struggle for equity, harmony, peace, and justice in Medford and beyond.

752
01:58:45,776 --> 01:59:00,945
So here with a charge, a mission statement, so to speak, for that hopeful future is our friend, WMCC board member and longtime senior pastor of West Medford Baptist Church, Reverend David M. Kilpatrick.

753
01:59:19,101 --> 01:59:24,004
Gary asked me if I would share some reflections on Martin Luther King Jr.

754
01:59:24,165 --> 01:59:31,430
and his legacy, but before I do that, let me share some personal remarks with you.

755
01:59:32,570 --> 01:59:37,214
I think I'm the only person in this room that knew Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

756
01:59:37,274 --> 01:59:37,894
personally.

757
01:59:39,355 --> 01:59:43,558
In the early 1960s, I was a seminary student in Rochester, New York.

758
01:59:44,759 --> 01:59:46,300
In those days, Rochester

759
01:59:47,049 --> 01:59:49,410
was owned by the Eastman Kodak Company.

760
01:59:50,370 --> 01:59:55,251
Nothing happened in Rochester unless it had the stamp of the Kodak Company on it.

761
01:59:56,372 --> 01:59:59,973
Nothing politically, nothing socially, nothing culturally.

762
02:00:01,213 --> 02:00:04,234
And the community needed to be organized.

763
02:00:04,394 --> 02:00:07,475
And a number of people came to town to help us to do that.

764
02:00:08,655 --> 02:00:12,796
One was the infamous Saul Alinensky, whom I'm sure you've heard about.

765
02:00:14,437 --> 02:00:16,117
But Martin came as well.

766
02:00:17,362 --> 02:00:27,426
And we put together a community coalition to organize the community of Rochester to advocate for itself.

767
02:00:28,846 --> 02:00:34,128
And as a young seminary student, I was on the steering committee of the coalition.

768
02:00:35,349 --> 02:00:38,810
And several times, we met together with Martin Luther King, Jr.

769
02:00:41,451 --> 02:00:43,492
Another interesting fact while I was there

770
02:00:44,848 --> 02:00:49,571
One week before he was assassinated, Malcolm X came to our seminary.

771
02:00:51,332 --> 02:00:54,514
He had recently been on a pilgrimage to Mecca.

772
02:00:56,715 --> 02:01:02,198
And on that pilgrimage, he rediscovered what the Muslim community is all about.

773
02:01:03,579 --> 02:01:13,125
People from all over the world, every size, shape, color, background, and realized what unity meant.

774
02:01:14,670 --> 02:01:17,152
And he and Martin had talked about that as well.

775
02:01:19,734 --> 02:01:25,919
And at that point in their histories, they shared a common vision of the beloved community.

776
02:01:27,581 --> 02:01:32,645
So in my reflections today, I'd like to share with you some thoughts about the beloved community.

777
02:01:34,786 --> 02:01:43,614
It's probably safe to say that for most of us as young children growing up, when it was time to celebrate the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.,

778
02:01:44,975 --> 02:01:49,236
He was mythologized, and he's still mythologized.

779
02:01:50,116 --> 02:02:00,698
We learned that Dr. King was a good man who had a dream that one day all would be treated equally and judged by the content of their character and not by the color of their skin.

780
02:02:01,598 --> 02:02:12,000
Most of us left those lessons believing that Dr. King had accomplished all that he set out to do, and that we live in a better America as a result.

781
02:02:13,693 --> 02:02:14,994
Sadly, that's not true.

782
02:02:16,875 --> 02:02:23,538
After all, we no longer see whites-only signs on water fountains and bathrooms in the South.

783
02:02:24,578 --> 02:02:29,641
And people of color can attend the same schools as European-American individuals.

784
02:02:31,081 --> 02:02:40,466
As we progressed in our schooling, however, some of us have been fortunate enough to be challenged by our educators to observe the ways in which race

785
02:02:42,563 --> 02:02:47,646
Our eyes may have been opened to the necessary continued work of the Civil Rights Movement.

786
02:02:48,467 --> 02:02:56,371
For many black Americans learning about Dr. King as the Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., he cannot drive out hate.

787
02:02:57,712 --> 02:02:58,973
Only love can do that.

788
02:03:00,433 --> 02:03:06,717
Refusing to disconnect his vision for the world from the Christian vision of peace and reconciliation.

789
02:03:08,230 --> 02:03:19,238
However, as Dr. King knew, we cannot get at reconciliation without first knowing and acknowledging the truth, some of which we've heard here today.

790
02:03:20,359 --> 02:03:32,388
The hard truth is that for protests and marches and outcries, that the lives of marches and outcries, that the lives of people of color matter.

791
02:03:33,569 --> 02:03:37,152
This is evident in the persistent of white supremacy

792
02:03:37,804 --> 02:03:44,948
and systemic racism that continue to deny equal rights and opportunities to people of color.

793
02:03:45,868 --> 02:03:52,691
Today, black college graduates are twice as likely to be unemployed from European-American college graduates.

794
02:03:53,652 --> 02:03:56,553
There's still an awful lot of work for us to do.

795
02:03:58,054 --> 02:04:05,958
Emphasis was placed on us because, as in the case of Dr. King, this cannot be the work of one individual

796
02:04:06,478 --> 02:04:11,219
or placed on the shoulders of even a small select group of people.

797
02:04:12,659 --> 02:04:21,201
Black youth activists and their allies played critical roles in propelling the movement forward and carrying out the work of Dr. King.

798
02:04:22,221 --> 02:04:29,742
A beloved community where there is no space for injustice or prejudice or discrimination.

799
02:04:30,862 --> 02:04:33,903
Rather, it's a space of economic and social justice

800
02:04:35,693 --> 02:04:40,515
The beloved community that Dr. King spoke about is more than just an ideology.

801
02:04:41,576 --> 02:04:50,060
In order for us to have such a beloved community, Dr. King said that we all must become outspoken champions.

802
02:04:51,460 --> 02:04:53,361
Outspoken champions.

803
02:04:54,281 --> 02:04:59,684
He warned that we are all complicit when we see injustice and do nothing about it.

804
02:05:00,789 --> 02:05:11,515
He reminded us that we have a moral obligation to stand up for racial and social justice and to dismantle systems of racism and discrimination.

805
02:05:12,775 --> 02:05:17,878
The late Congressman John Lewis, a disciple of Dr. King, shared these same sentiments.

806
02:05:18,838 --> 02:05:22,841
When you see something that is not right, you have to say something.

807
02:05:24,341 --> 02:05:25,442
You must do something.

808
02:05:26,556 --> 02:05:30,818
Each of us must do our part to help to build that beloved community.

809
02:05:32,098 --> 02:05:37,820
We can trace Dr. King's advocacy for the beloved community to his theology.

810
02:05:37,840 --> 02:05:45,483
And so today, in 2023, we affirm that all people are valuable in the eyes of God.

811
02:05:46,483 --> 02:05:55,126
While recognizing the historical injustices such as stealing of lands of indigenous peoples, the enslavement of Africans,

812
02:05:56,504 --> 02:06:10,634
concentrated poverty and the overall marginalization of minoritized groups, that all continues to play a role in how society is constructed and how we experience it.

813
02:06:11,715 --> 02:06:25,625
We believe that in order to fulfill the call to love God and to love our neighbors wholeheartedly, we must be attentive to the ways in which we can unintentionally perpetuate barriers

814
02:06:26,241 --> 02:06:30,845
that cause disparities and alienate already marginalized people.

815
02:06:31,946 --> 02:06:46,800
Implicit biases, microaggressions, exclusionary or exploitative policies and practices, ignorance of irrelevant cultural events pervade our culture predominantly.

816
02:06:47,841 --> 02:06:52,285
What institutions, as a Christ-centered community,

817
02:06:53,453 --> 02:07:06,061
and a religious-centered community, we must be attentive to these dynamics and dismantle systems that dehumanize people, as we are all created in the Imago Dei.

818
02:07:07,162 --> 02:07:21,491
In the context of community, we believe that the work of diversity and belonging is not only important in creating an inclusive environment where everybody can thrive, but also in allowing the community to demonstrate

819
02:07:22,315 --> 02:07:23,396
our religious faith.

820
02:07:24,536 --> 02:07:44,727
By celebrating the diversity of our community while also seeking to explicitly address racial and social disparities, we believe that we can reflect the love of God toward others and serve as a beacon of hope in a society that is still plagued by division and prejudice and hate.

821
02:07:45,647 --> 02:07:50,290
It's only through creating this kind of life-giving and hospitable community

822
02:07:50,937 --> 02:08:04,511
that we can really honor Dr. King's legacy, and in his words, bring to fruition the day when all God's children will be able to join hands and redeem

823
02:08:23,838 --> 02:08:25,579
So I love my brother Pastor.

824
02:08:25,599 --> 02:08:27,960
He was my father's pastor for many, many years.

825
02:08:28,840 --> 02:08:40,465
And when a pastor says, can you give me two minutes, and you say yes, and then he turns to the next person and says, can you give me two minutes, and he says yes, and he turns to the next person and says, can you give me two minutes, and he says yes, he says, OK, I got six minutes.

826
02:08:42,045 --> 02:08:43,686
Thank you very much for your reflections.

827
02:08:43,706 --> 02:08:46,847
They definitely were important to the day.

828
02:08:50,289 --> 02:08:53,090
I want to welcome Stacey Clayton back to the stage

829
02:08:53,644 --> 02:09:00,209
to lead us in James Weldon Johnson's anthem of Black America, Lift Every Voice and Sing.

830
02:09:00,650 --> 02:09:11,198
For those of you that don't know the words, we've placed copies of the lyrics at each table, so I'm gonna set it up on the audio and the mic to Stacy.

831
02:09:14,120 --> 02:09:21,867
As we're standing as your people, and we're getting ready, preparing our hearts to sing, lift every voice and sing.

832
02:09:22,597 --> 02:09:30,181
my two senses, make sure that we're intentional at making every voice be at that table.

833
02:09:30,341 --> 02:09:39,666
And as we sing, can we reflect on experiences in our own lives where we're serving at a table where we don't see or hear every voice.

834
02:09:40,377 --> 02:09:47,501
And one of the things that this song can kind of help us to remember is to help every voice to be lifted.

